6. THIRD Donm: The Law being promulgated, when does it begin to oblige the subject?

First3 Those Laws which specify a time at which they come into action oblige from that time3 and continue to oblige for ever, except the time of their obligation is defined by the Law itself, or they are abrogated by new Laws, or by contrary customs. [On this last point, see Prael. vn. Sect. 25]. In the Imperial Roman Law it was pro- vided, by an express Rule, that new Laws did not oblige the subJect till two months after their promulgation: in which time it was pre- sumed they might come to the knowledge of all the subjects of the emp1re.
